Here are the implementation steps for applying the query-fix config to both nodes. I'll keep it sequential and safe — Node 1 first, verify, then Node 2.

## Pre-checks (before you start)

```bash
# Confirm current cluster is healthy before changing anything
curl -s http://10.189.35.10:3100/ring | grep -c ACTIVE     # expect 4
curl -s http://10.189.35.11:3100/ring | grep -c ACTIVE     # expect 4
```
If both show 4, proceed. The two new config files are the ones I generated: `node1-loki-config.yaml` and `node2-loki-config.yaml`.

## Node 1

```bash
cd /root/dclogforward1/multi-node/node1

# 1. Back up the current working config
cp loki-config.yaml loki-config.yaml.bak.$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S)

# 2. Put the new config in place (transfer node1-loki-config.yaml here first,
#    then rename it over the existing file)
cp node1-loki-config.yaml loki-config.yaml

# 3. (Optional) sanity-check it's valid YAML before restarting
docker run --rm -v "$PWD/loki-config.yaml:/c.yaml:ro" grafana/loki:3.5.5 \
  -config.file=/c.yaml -verify-config -config.expand-env=true 2>&1 | tail -5 || true

# 4. Recreate so the mounted config is reloaded
docker compose down && docker compose --profile redis up -d
```

**Verify Node 1 before touching Node 2:**
```bash
sleep 30
# Ring back to 4 ACTIVE
curl -s http://10.189.35.10:3100/ring | grep -c ACTIVE

# All components ready
for p in 3100 3101 3102 3103 3104 3105 3106 3107; do
  echo -n "node1:$p -> "; curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}\n" http://10.189.35.10:$p/ready
done

# New query settings actually loaded
curl -s http://10.189.35.10:3100/config | grep -iE "split_queries_by_interval|query_timeout|cache_results|max_outstanding"
```
Expect `split_queries_by_interval: 1h`, `query_timeout: 5m`, `cache_results: true`, `max_outstanding_per_tenant: 2048`. Only continue if Node 1 is healthy and shows these values.

## Node 2 (only after Node 1 is confirmed good)

```bash
cd /root/dclogforward1/multi-node/node2

cp loki-config.yaml loki-config.yaml.bak.$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S)
cp node2-loki-config.yaml loki-config.yaml

docker run --rm -v "$PWD/loki-config.yaml:/c.yaml:ro" grafana/loki:3.5.5 \
  -config.file=/c.yaml -verify-config -config.expand-env=true 2>&1 | tail -5 || true

docker compose down && docker compose --profile redis up -d
```

**Verify Node 2:**
```bash
sleep 30
curl -s http://10.189.35.11:3100/ring | grep -c ACTIVE          # expect 4
curl -s http://10.189.35.11:3100/config | grep -iE "split_queries_by_interval|query_timeout|cache_results|max_outstanding"
```

## Final cluster-wide validation

```bash
# Both nodes see the same 4 ACTIVE ingesters
curl -s http://10.189.35.10:3100/ring | grep -c ACTIVE
curl -s http://10.189.35.11:3100/ring | grep -c ACTIVE

# Memberlist converged (14 on both)
curl -s http://10.189.35.10:3100/memberlist | grep -c "10.189.35"
curl -s http://10.189.35.11:3100/memberlist | grep -c "10.189.35"

# Ingestion still healthy — no rate-limit rejections
docker logs --since 5m loki-distributor-primary-1-node1 2>&1 | grep -ic "rate limit exceeded"

# The actual test: a wide (2-day) query that used to fail, with a narrow selector
curl -s -G "http://10.189.35.10:3104/loki/api/v1/query_range" \
  --data-urlencode 'query={kubernetes_namespace_name="prod-dc-transaction"}' \
  --data-urlencode "start=$(date -d '2 days ago' +%s)000000000" \
  --data-urlencode "end=$(date +%s)000000000" \
  --data-urlencode "limit=1000" | head -c 300; echo
```
A `"status":"success"` with results = the query fix works. Then confirm the same in the **Grafana UI** with a 1-hour and a 2-day range.

## If something goes wrong — rollback

The backups make this safe. On either node:
```bash
cd /root/dclogforward1/multi-node/node<N>
cp loki-config.yaml.bak.<timestamp> loki-config.yaml
docker compose down && docker compose --profile redis up -d
```

## Notes

- **Redis:** keep using `--profile redis` exactly as before. As discussed, the embedded cache handles this fix; the Redis container just idles. No change needed there.
- **One node at a time** is important — with RF=2, keeping Node 1's ingesters serving while Node 2 restarts means no gap in log ingestion.
- The `-verify-config` step is optional but a good safety net; if it errors, it'll be because of an env var it can't expand in standalone mode — in that case just skip it and rely on the post-restart `/config` check, which is the real confirmation.

Once both nodes show the new settings in `/config` and the 2-day test query returns success, you're done. Share the sizing output whenever ready and I'll confirm the queriers can handle the increased parallelism under your real load.
